EpisodeNarrative: An avalanche in-bounds at the Canyons Resort caught 4 skiers in it, leading to three injuries and one fatality.
EventNarrative: A 30 year-old male was killed in an avalanche at the Canyons Resort. The avalanche was triggered by two men who were descending upper Red Pine Chute;  one of the men was caught by the slide, but ended up on top of the snow.  The other man was caught and died of head trauma after hitting a tree.  A man and a child below were engulfed, with the man partially buried, and the child totally buried. The child was hospitalized for several days following the avalanche, but survived his injuries.

A deep, occluded low pressure system moved northeast across Western Upper Michigan during the daylight hours of the 23rd.  As colder air entered the region, rain turned to snow.  Southwest winds off of Lake Michigan enhanced snowfall into parts of Northwest Lower Michigan.  Places west of Cadillac and Traverse City picked up three to eight inches of snowfall, with eight in Wellston, and nearly seven in Honor and Suttons Bay.  Gusty winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow.  A few gusts of 40 to 50 mph produced spotty power outages near Manistee and Cadillac.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong cold front was traversing across the Ohio Valley during the early morning hours of December 23rd. This strong front crossed eastern Pennsylvania during the evening hours. A southerly flow turned gusty ahead of this front, then winds peaked once again with the passage of the cold front later in the evening. The strongest winds generally occurred between 3 PM EST and 9 PM EST on the 23rd. Peak wind gusts included 46 mph in Reading (Berks County) and 45 mph in Mount Pocono (Monroe County). Peak wind gusts were lower farther southeast in the Lehigh Valley and the local Philadelphia area.

EpisodeNarrative: The long-duration winter storm of December 22-23rd that affected the counties of Marquette, Sauk, Iowa, and Lafayette, subsided to a winter weather event during the evening hours of December 23rd.  Some minor to moderate blowing and drifting snow continued as west-southwest winds of 25 to 32 knots (30 to 37 mph) gusted to 30 to 49 knots (35 to 45 mph).  Visibilities in open rural areas was occasionally reduced to 1/2 to 3/4 mile.  Refer to a Strong Wind event for December 23rd for related wind information.  Synoptically, low pressure deepened rapidly as it moved northeast through southeast Wisconsin on its way to the Upper Penesula of Michigan.

EpisodeNarrative: A powerful upper level and surface storm system moved from the Great Lakes on December 23rd across Ontario and Quebec during the 24th.  Accompanying this system were strong winds in excess of 70 to 80 mph between 3000 and 6000 feet above the surface. Meanwhile, at the surface, a strong warm and cold front associated with this powerful storm moved across northern New York during the late afternoon and evening hours of the 23rd. The development of rain showers along the cold front during the evening hours allowed for some of these strong winds to reach the surface which caused localized wind damage in the form of downed branches, trees and scattered power outages as well as damaged loose holiday lawn ornaments in southern portions of the northern Adirondacks in communities like Fine (St. Lawrence county), Tupper Lake and Saranac Lake (Franklin county) and Lake Placid (Essex county).
EventNarrative: Tree branches and power lines reported downed by high winds in southeast St. Lawrence county near Fine.

EpisodeNarrative: A deep low moved into the Great Lakes Region resulting in a dramatic warm-up into the 50s and over an inch of soaking rain. This unleashed snowmelt of the 4 to 7 inch snowpack, with lower elevations of the Niagara Frontier bare by late in the day. Rivers and creeks swelled with three Buffalo area creeks (Cazenovia, Buffalo and Cayuga) going over Flood Stage during the evening of the 23rd. Cazenovia Creek at Ebenezer (Flood Stage 10 feet) crested at 10.8 feet. Cayuga Creek at Lancaster (Flood Stage 8 feet) crested at 8.4 feet. Buffalo Creek at Gardenville (Flood Stage 7 feet) crested at 7.3 feet. Only minor flooding was reported and no significant damage occurred.

A cold front associated with this low pressure system swept east across eastern New York and western New England late Sunday afternoon and evening.||Strong to locally damaging winds occurred ahead of, and with the cold frontal passage on Sunday.
EventNarrative: Numerous power outages were reported in Whitehall as a result of downed tree limbs and wires from high winds.

EpisodeNarrative: A deep low moved into the Great Lakes Region resulting in a dramatic warm-up into the 50s and over an inch of soaking rain. This unleashed snowmelt of the 4 to 7 inch snowpack, with lower elevations of the Niagara Frontier bare by late in the day. Rivers and creeks swelled with three Buffalo area creeks (Cazenovia, Buffalo and Cayuga) going over Flood Stage during the evening of the 23rd. Cazenovia Creek at Ebenezer (Flood Stage 10 feet) crested at 10.8 feet. Cayuga Creek at Lancaster (Flood Stage 8 feet) crested at 8.4 feet. Buffalo Creek at Gardenville (Flood Stage 7 feet) crested at 7.3 feet. Only minor flooding was reported and no significant damage occurred.

EpisodeNarrative: A powerful upper level and surface storm system across the Great Lakes on December 23rd moved across Ontario and Quebec during the 24th. Accompanying this system were strong winds in excess of 70 to 80 mph between 3000 and 6000 feet above the surface. Meanwhile, at the surface, a strong warm and cold front associated with this powerful storm moved across Vermont during the evening hours of the 23rd. The development of rain showers along the cold front during the evening hours allowed for some of these strong winds to reach the surface which caused localized wind damage in the form of downed branches, trees and scattered power outages as well as damaged loose holiday lawn ornaments in Cambridge (Lamoille county), Montgomery (eastern Franklin county) as well as Jay, Irasburg and Coventry (Orleans county). In addition, there was an unofficial anenometer reading of 84 mph in Cambridge.
EventNarrative: Unofficial observed wind gust of 84 mph as reported by anemometer approximately 30 feet above the surface in Pleasant Valley/Cambridge.

EpisodeNarrative: A potent cold front crossed the region during the afternoon hours. Behind the front, windy conditions developed. Scattered power outages were reported across the western parts of the Niagara Frontier and the strong winds were funneled over Lake Erie. Sustained winds to 40 mph were measured at Niagara Falls International Airport and gusts to 61 mph were measured at Buffalo Niagara International Airport.
Heavy rain associated with the passage of a strong cold front in combination with a melting snow pack caused the Mahwah River at Suffern to overflow its' banks.
EventNarrative: The Mahwah River at Suffern exceeded its' flood stage of 4 feet on Dec. 23, 2007 at 8:45 pm with a stage of 4.12 feet. The river crested at 5.65 feet on Dec. 24, 2007 at 12:30 am and returned within its banks on Dec 24, 2007 at 1:30 pm.

EventNarrative: The Ho-Ho-Kus River at Ho-Ho-Kus exceeded its' flood stage of 3.0 feet on Dec. 23, 2007 at 9:30 pm with a stage of 3.03 feet. The river crested at 3.31 feet on Dec. 23, 2007 at 11:15 pm and returned within its' banks on Dec. 24, 2007 at 1:45 pm.

EpisodeNarrative: The combination of a steady rain and snow and ice melt on the 23rd helped produce stream and river flooding in parts of Somerset and Morris Counties later in the day on the 23rd into the early morning on the 25th. The heaviest rain fell between 3 pm EST and 9 pm EST that day. Storm totals averaged between 1 and 2 inches. Most of the stream and river flooding occurred in the northwest part of Somerset County and the northeast part of Morris County. The rain was caused by a strong low pressure system which moved from the upper Mississippi Valley on the morning of the 22nd, through the Great Lakes on the 23rd and into Quebec Province, Canada by the morning of the 24th. A strong high pressure system off the Canadian Maritimes on the 23rd assisted in pumping Atlantic Ocean moisture into this system.
EventNarrative: The North Branch of the Raritan River at the Village of South Branch was above its 7 foot flood stage from 955 p.m. EST on the 23rd through 746 a.m. EST on the 24th. It crested at 8.86 feet at 315 a.m. EST on the 24th. The Lamington River at Burnt Mills was above its 9.5 foot flood stage from 930 p.m. EST on the 23rd through 200 a.m. EST on the 24th. It crested at 10.1 feet at Midnight EST on the 24th.||Specific storm totals included 1.68 inches in Neshanic, 1.24 inches in Pottersville and 1.16 inches in Somerville.

EventNarrative: The Pompton River at Midwood Road in Lincoln Park was above its 8.5 foot flood stage from 3 a.m. EST through 840 a.m. EST on the 24th. It crested at 8.7 feet at 8 a.m. EST. The Rockaway River below the Boonton Reservoir was above its 5 foot flood stage from 1022 a.m. EST on the 24th through 153 a.m. EST on the 25th. It crested at 5.23 feet at 330 p.m. EST on the 24th. EpisodeNarrative: Strong winds occurred as a potent cold front crossed Eastern Kentucky on December 23rd. A couple of trees, a few tree branches, and a couple of power lines were brought down by the strong winds. Wind gusts ranged from a measured peak gust of 48 mph at Monticello Airport, to a much lower gust of 31 mph measured at the Hazard Airport.
EventNarrative: Numerous tree branches, several greater than 2 inches in diameter, were blown down by strong winds in Relief.

EpisodeNarrative: A storm system moving through the region caused strong low pressure to form over Alberta. As a result, very strong winds occurred in the favored areas of the Beartooth and Absaroka Mountains. In addition, a strong cold front moved across the forecast area bringing in much cooler temperatures. The mountains experienced the heaviest snowfall late Christmas Eve into Christmas morning as a result of an unstable airmass that allowed for rapid accumulations. Windy conditions also contributed to areas of blowing and drifting snow. The following snow totals were received: 9 inches 10WSW Limestone(Placer Basin Snotel), 6 inches 2S Otter and in Otter and 8 inches 5NE Ridge.
EventNarrative: East Livingston DOT measured 50 mph sustained winds.

EpisodeNarrative: A Pacific storm system and associated cold front caused heavy snow and considerable wind across western Wyoming on Christmas Eve.  Snowfall of around six inches was reported in the Star Valley with slightly more than one foot in the nearby mountains.  As the storm moved east of the Continental Divide it brought favorable northerly upslope flow to the Lander Foothills.  A quick six to eight inches of snow was recorded by early Christmas morning in and near Lander.

Strong winds developed in advance of a cold front crossing Maine. Wind gusts of 45 to 55 mph were common across Downeast areas. Higher gusts occurred with onshore winds near the coast where winds occasionally gusted to around 60 mph. A peak wind gust of 61 mph was reported at Cutler in coastal Washington county. The winds toppled some trees and power lines leading to power outages...with around a thousand customers losing power.
EventNarrative: Trees were blown down in the Whitneyville and Jonesboro areas. A wind gust of 61 mph was measured at Cutler.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong storm moved across Kodiak Island December 24th to the northern Gulf of Alaska. Snow fell in advance of the low across Kodiak island spreading to the southern Kenai Peninsula. Strong wind associated with this storm combined with the snow to produce blizzard conditions across lake Iliamna followed by blizzard conditions across Kodiak island. Heavy snow fell over the southern Kenai Peninsula to Portage pass. The strong wind hit those areas producing blizzard conditions in the pass and along Turnagain Arm.
EventNarrative: Homer Flight Service reported 14 inches of snow fell along Dimond Ridge.

EpisodeNarrative: The arctic front had become stationary over northern southeast Alaska on Monday, 12/24 while a storm force low center had moved into the western Gulf that afternoon. A series of fronts slowly moved onshore from this low causing warm, moist air to move over the arctic front on Tuesday, 12/25.
EventNarrative: Haines customs observed 9.0 inches of new snowfall for 24 hours ending 0800 on 12/25. Analyses showed that most, if not all of the snow fell between 0300 and 0800 on Tuesday, 12/25.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong storm moved across Kodiak Island December 24th to the northern Gulf of Alaska. Snow fell in advance of the low across Kodiak island spreading to the southern Kenai Peninsula. Strong wind associated with this storm combined with the snow to produce blizzard conditions across lake Iliamna followed by blizzard conditions across Kodiak island. Heavy snow fell over the southern Kenai Peninsula to Portage pass. The strong wind hit those areas producing blizzard conditions in the pass and along Turnagain Arm.

EpisodeNarrative: Strong offshore flow on Christmas Day caused sporadic power outages, uprooted trees, and overturned semi-tractor trailer rigs. The strongest winds were confined to areas below the Cajon Pass in the Inland Empire and in the Santa Ana Mountains and Foothills.
EventNarrative: Wind gusts in excess of 58 mph were measured by the Fremont Canyon RAWS for nine consecutive hours. A peak wind gust of 85 mph occurred at 1030 PST.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong cold front brought gusty winds to the mountains of southern Nevada.
EventNarrative: A measured gust to 58 mph occurred at the Red Rock RAWS.

EpisodeNarrative: Strong offshore flow on Christmas Day caused sporadic power outages, uprooted trees, and overturned semi-tractor trailer rigs. The strongest winds were confined to areas below the Cajon Pass in the Inland Empire and in the Santa Ana Mountains and Foothills.
EventNarrative: A 58 mph wind gust was measured at Ontario Airport. Gusty winds in the Inland Empire downed power lines, uprooted trees, and overturned high profile vehicles.

EpisodeNarrative: A winter storm brought heavy snow to the Front Range of Colorado on Christmas day.  The heaviest snow fell in and near the foothills of Boulder, Douglas and Jefferson Counties.  The snow triggered accidents throughout Denver and the surrounding metropolitan area.  Gusty winds stirred snow drifts from 2 to 3.5 feet in depth.  Officially, the total calendar day snowfall for Denver was 7.8 inches, setting the record for Christmas Day.  The previous record was 6.2 inches, established in 1894.  ||Storm totals in the Front Range Foothills:  13.5 inches at Coal Creek Canyon, Genesee and 3 miles east-southeast of Tiny Town; 12.5 inches, 4 miles east-northeast of Conifer; 12 inches, 5 miles east-southeast of Aspen Park; 11 inches, 6 miles southwest of Kassler; 10.5 inches at Eldorado Springs.  Elsewhere, storm totals range from with 5 to 10 inches.||In the Urban Corridor storm totals included:  9 inches near Elizabeth; 8 inches in southwest Denver, Highlands Ranch, Marston Reservoir and Wheat Ridge; 7.5 inches in Arvada; 7 inches in Centennial and Lakewood; 6.5 inches in Aurora and 8 miles southeast of Watkins; 6 inches in Boulder, Englewood and Parker.  Elsewhere, snowfall totals ranged from 3 to 5 inches.
EventNarrative: Storm totals generally ranged from 2 to 5 inches.  Locally higher amounts from 8 to 11 inches were observed in the foothills of southern Boulder County.

EpisodeNarrative: An avalanche in a popular snowmobiling area killed one man.
EventNarrative: A 53 year-old man, who was snowmobiling with his family, was caught in an avalanche, buried by the snow, and died before being found. The avalanche occurred at a common spot for snowmobilers near Windy Ridge called Superbowl. No other injuries were reported.

EpisodeNarrative: A vigorous upper low moved southeast across New Mexico while a strong cold front plunged south across the eastern plains.  A narrow band of moderate to heavy snow and blowing snow developed during the evening of the 25th, with snowfall of 2 to 5 inches and reduced visibility in blowing snow.  Numerous vehicles went off the roadway along Interstate 40 between Clines Corners and Tucumcari.  Heavy snow was also reported in Fort Sumner.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong low moved up to the Alaska Peninsula the night of December 25th producing very strong wind across the peninsula. Wind gusts reached 75 mph in Cold Bay damaging buildings and roofs in Cold Bay and King Cove.

A fast moving storm system brought accumulating snowfall to a broad area of the Southern Plains during the early morning hours of the 26th. Although the west Texas South Plains was on the periphery of this storm, light snow accumulations were observed over the extreme southwestern Texas Panhandle and the northern South Plains. Reports of 1 inch or greater accumulations included: 2 inches at Rhea (Parmer County), 1 inch at Caprock Canyon State Park (Briscoe County), 1 inch at Floydada (Floyd County), 1 inch at Plainview (Hale County), and 1 inch at Silverton (Briscoe County).

A weak area of low pressure moved through central California during the evening of December 25th. The main impacts were to bring a few showers to the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains (including the foothills). Behind the weak low pressure, gusty winds developed over the mountains and deserts, with numerous gusts to 50 mph, and a peak wind gust of 75 mph measured at the Mojave Air/Spaceport. ||The strong winds around 75 mph in the desert caused a dust storm to occur in the Lancaster and Mojave areas on the 26th. Law enforcement shut down portions of the Antelope Valley Freeway north of Lancaster, as well as Highway 58 through much of eastern Kern County in the desert. Strong winds also caused a tractor-trailer to overturn along California Highway 14 at California City Blvd.

Another in a series of quick moving upper level systems moved through Oklahoma as residents packed shopping malls the day after Christmas. This system was similar to the one that passed through the region several days earlier, with a quick burst of moderate to heavy snow. Snowfall totals were generally one to three inches, and these occurred mainly over central Oklahoma. However, isolated locations in Seminole and Pottawatomie counties received four to six inches. Due to the time of day that the precipitation occurred, several accidents occurred, but few injuries were reported. Monetary damages were estimated.
EventNarrative: The area near the Twin Lakes WSR-88D received two inches of snow.

Snowfall totals were generally one to three inches, and these occurred mainly over central Oklahoma. However, isolated locations in Seminole and Pottawatomie counties received four to six inches. Due to the time of day that the precipitation occurred, several accidents occurred, but few injuries were reported. Monetary damages were estimated.
EventNarrative: A measured amount of 1.5 inches of snow fell at the National Weather Center.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong upper level low pressure center tracked northeastward across Arkansas on the 26th. In much of western and northern Arkansas, temperatures were just cold enough to allow some sleet and snow to fall.
EventNarrative: Snow fell in the county. A light dusting was reported at Dardanelle, 2 to 3 inches were reported at Danville, and 1 to 2 inches were reported at Ola.

EpisodeNarrative: A weak area of low pressure moved through central California during the evening of December 25th. The main impacts were to bring a few showers to the Southern Sierra Nevada and Tehachapi Mountains (including the foothills). Behind the weak low pressure, gusty winds developed over the mountains and deserts, with numerous gusts to 50 mph, and a peak wind gust of 75 mph measured at the Mojave Air/Spaceport. ||The strong winds around 75 mph in the desert caused a dust storm to occur in the Lancaster and Mojave areas on the 26th. Law enforcement shut down portions of the Antelope Valley Freeway north of Lancaster, as well as Highway 58 through much of eastern Kern County in the desert. Strong winds also caused a tractor-trailer to overturn along California Highway 14 at California City Blvd.
A low pressure trough moving slowly across the Upper Great Lakes brought moderate snow to portions of western Upper Michigan on the 25th and 26th.
EventNarrative: Mohawk reported inch per hour snowfall rates and measured 5.5 inches of total snowfall.

EpisodeNarrative: Isolated strong to severe thunderstorms affected areas of southeast Louisiana as a strong upper level disturbance moved across the lower Mississippi Valley.
EventNarrative: A weak tornado briefly touched down causing minor to moderate damage to five houses and two mobile homes. The damage to the houses was mainly to the roofs. A shed was also destroyed. The tornado traveled across Mark Street and Melvin Street off of Bayou Dularge Road.

EpisodeNarrative: A low over the central Bering Sea and another low near Kodiak Island helped to produce strong winds over western Alaska. A weather front from the Bering Sea low moved north over Eastern Norton sound and briefly produced high winds at Unalakleet, where the AWOS reported a maximum gust of 53 knots (61 mph).

EpisodeNarrative: Sussex County was on the northwest fringe of the precipitation shield associated with a coastal low pressure system during the night of the 26th. The higher terrain locations failed to rise above freezing as shots of light precipitation moved through. While it was warm enough aloft for precipitation to fall as rain, it froze on contact across some of the higher terrain locations in Sussex County. Since precipitation amounts were light, ice accretions were mostly just a trace. But, untreated walkways and roadways were slippery.

The Poconos were on the northwest fringe of the precipitation shield associated with a coastal low pressure system during the night of the 26th. They were also along the southern fringe of precipitation associated with a low pressure system that was approaching from the west. The higher terrain locations failed to rise above freezing as shots of light precipitation moved through. While it was warm enough aloft for precipitation to fall as rain, it froze on contact across some of the higher terrain locations in the Poconos. Since precipitation amounts were light, ice accretions were mostly just a trace. But, untreated walkways and roadways were slippery.  This same system produced sleet during the evening of the 26th across Berks County, the Lehigh Valley and the Philadelphia northwest suburbs. Temperatures in those areas were above freezing.

Another in a series of cold, moist Pacific frontal systems brought heavy snow to the Cascades and Cascade Foothills, and to the Upper Hood River Valley, building the steadily increasing mountain snow pack.  Lighter amounts fell in other areas of the forecast area. This frontal system also brought localized strong and gusty winds to the coastline.
EventNarrative: Recorded in Florence. Sustained winds of 42 kt were also reported.

EpisodeNarrative: Another winter storm brought heavy snow to portions of the Urban Corridor and Northeast Plains. Storm totals generally ranged from 3 to 7 inches, with locally heavier bands producing up to 11 inches of snowfall.  ||Along the Urban Corridor storm totals included:  11 inches, 7 miles southeast of Loveland; 10 inches at 3 miles west of Berthoud, 10 miles south-southeast of Buckley AFB and Castle Pines; 9.5 inches 4 miles south-southeast of Aurora and Kassler; 8.5 inches near Bellvue and Ft. Collins; 7.5 inches, 2 miles southeast of Highlands Ranch; 7 inches in Aurora and Sedalia; 6.5 inches in Arvada, 4 miles east of Denver and Lafayette; 6 inches at Castle Rock and Thornton.||Across the Northeast Plains storm totals included:  9 inches in Greeley; 8 inches at Hugo and 3 miles northeast of Wiggins; 7.5 inches, 4 miles west-southwest of Eaton; 7 inches at Ft. Morgan, Karval, and Windsor; 6.5 inches at Agate; 6 inches at Arriba and 6 miles south of New Raymer.
EventNarrative: Storm totals ranged from 5 to 11 inches.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong low over the southwest end of Kodiak Island produced a strong west to northwest wind regime across the Alaska Peninsula resulting in strong damaging wind.
EventNarrative: The observed peak wind at Cold Bay was 69 mph. Based upon this observed peak gust and the associated damage reported around Cold Bay.

EpisodeNarrative: Yet another cold front brought heavy snow to Oregon.  This time the snow fell at unusually low elevations. Snow Advisories were in effect for this event, but no warnings were issued. Some locations did report snow amounts meeting Heavy Snow Warning criteria.
EventNarrative: A spotter 1N of Shady Cove reported 3.5 inches of snow in 10 hours ending at 27/1600 PST.

EpisodeNarrative: A winter storm produced heavy snowfall with accumulations of 5-10 inches across eastern Colorado and portions of western Kansas.
EventNarrative: Six to ten inches of snow was reported across the SW half of Yuma county with lesser amounts in the north and east. Ten inches was reported in the Joes area.

EpisodeNarrative: A winter storm produced heavy snowfall with accumulations of 5-10 inches across eastern Colorado and portions of western Kansas.
EventNarrative: Three to nine inches of snow was reported across Kit Carson county with greatest accumulations in the west near Flagler.

EpisodeNarrative: Another in a series of cold, moist Pacific frontal systems brought heavy snow to the Cascades and Cascade Foothills, and to the Upper Hood River Valley, building the steadily increasing mountain snow pack.  Lighter amounts fell in other areas of the forecast area. This frontal system also brought localized strong and gusty winds to the coastline.
EventNarrative: Seven inches total snowfall accumulation were reported in Dee.

EventNarrative: The tower at Fort Lauderdale International Airport observed a funnel cloud with a line of showers just offshore the coast of Fort Lauderdale Beach. The funnel cloud only lasted a few minutes before dissipating, and never touched the surface.

Some minor tidal flooding occurred during the morning high tide in Monmouth County on the 27th. The high tide at Sandy Hook (Monmouth County) reached 6.84 feet above mean lower low water. Minor tidal flooding starts at 6.70 feet above mean lower low water.  The low pressure system which caused the onshore flow moved northeast from the North Carolina coastal waters on the morning of the 26th to the coastal waters off of the Delmarva peninsula on the evening of the 26th. It continued to move northeast and passed just to the southeast of the Nantucket buoy on the morning of the 27th. The longer onshore flow through the high tide cycle helped caused the minor tidal flooding farther north in New Jersey.

A very dynamic storm system brought a variety of severe weather impacts to the South Plains of west Texas late on the 27th. ||Moist and sub-freezing upslope northeasterly flow behind a cold front resulted in persistent ice fog through much of the day over the extreme southeastern Texas Panhandle, particularly along the Caprock Escarpment. Although ice accumulated on most exposed surfaces, no adverse impacts were reported.||By late afternoon, weather impacts became much more intense and diverse. An area of heavy snow developed over the extreme southwestern Texas Panhandle and the northwestern South Plains. The area of wintry precipitation quickly moved northeastward, but not before accumulating snows occurred over the area and resulted in treacherous travel conditions. Roadways, including major interstate highways, became snowpacked - and remained dangerous through much of the morning hours on the 28th. ||Reported snow accumulations follow:  4 inches at Happy (Swisher County), 3 inches at Lazbuddie (Parmer County), 3 inches at Tulia (Swisher County), 2 inches at Nazareth (Castro County), 1 inch at Dimmitt (Castro County), 1 inch at Plainview (Hale County), and 1 inch at Silverton (Briscoe County).||South of the snow band, strong winds advected eastward behind a dryline-like feature that moved over the western and central South Plains. Wind gusts in excess of 40 mph were recorded at a number of Texas Tech University West Texas Mesonet sites over the western South Plains. Wind contributed to the failure of a metal shed building in northwest Lubbock. In addition, two non-mesocyclonic tornadoes were observed and photographed in the Lubbock vicinity. These tornadoes developed near a deepening surface low and its associated surface boundaries, and beneath towering cumulus clouds within a strongly unstable low-level airmass. No measurable precipitation occurred in association with the tornadic cumuliform clouds.

A very strong Pacific jet dug south into the four corners region late Wednesday, December 26th, allowing a significant winter storm to form over the southern Rockies.  This storm then moved into western Kansas during Thursday afternoon, December 27th, and crossed through into central Kansas Thursday evening.  The heaviest snow fell in far western Kansas, dumping 5to 6 inches from north of Coolidge in Hamilton County south to near the Saunders Elevator in southwest Stanton County.  A 20 to 35 mile wide swath of 4 to 5 inches of snow fell from north of Syracuse in Hamilton County southward to near Big Bow in eastern Stanton County to western Morton County west of Richfield.   Another 20 mile wide band of 4 to 5 inch snow fell from southeast Kearny County to southeast of Sublette in Haskell County.  A large area of 2 to 4 inches of snow fell across the remainder of DDC???s CWA, except in eastern Morton and western Steven Counties where only 1 to 2 inches of snow fell.

A very strong Pacific jet dug south into the four corners region late Wednesday, December 26th, allowing a significant winter storm to form over the southern Rockies.  This storm then moved into western Kansas during Thursday afternoon, December 27th, and crossed through into central Kansas Thursday evening.  The heaviest snow fell in far western Kansas, dumping 5to 6 inches from north of Coolidge in Hamilton County south to near the Saunders Elevator in southwest Stanton County.  A 20 to 35 mile wide swath of 4 to 5 inches of snow fell from north of Syracuse in Hamilton County southward to near Big Bow in eastern Stanton County to western Morton County west of Richfield.   Another 20 mile wide band of 4 to 5 inch snow fell from southeast Kearny County to southeast of Sublette in Haskell County.  A large area of 2 to 4 inches of snow fell across the remainder of DDC???s CWA, except in eastern Morton and western Steven Counties where only 1 to 2 inches of snow fell.

A vigorous Pacific storm system brought heavy snowfall to central Oregon and the Blue Mountains.  Blizzard conditions were observed in the Grande Ronde Valley which closed Interstate 84 for several hours. At the Ladd Canyon rest area visibility frequently was below 1/4 mile with wind gusts 35-53 mph between 10 pm and 6 am.  Snowfall in inches included Tollgate (8), 2 miles east of Meacham (15), LaPine (6.5), 12 miles east northeast of LaPine (12).

Strong winds in the mid levels of the atmosphere, in advance of an upper level storm system, moved across portions of west Texas.  This resulted in high winds across the Guadalupe and Davis Mountains.
EventNarrative: Wind equipment at McDonald Observatory reported at peak wind of 71 mph at 9 pm CST, Thursday evening.

EpisodeNarrative: Strong winds in the mid levels of the atmosphere, in advance of an upper level storm system, moved across portions of west Texas.  This resulted in high winds across the Guadalupe and Davis Mountains.
EventNarrative: The ASOS at Guadalupe Pass reported a 78 mph gust Thursday afternoon.

EpisodeNarrative: A storm moved into the Bering Sea as a second low associated with this storm moved into the Gulf of Alaska. The resulting strong west wind flow produced a storm surge along the Bristol Bay coast during the high tide that resulted in flooding in the community of Pilot Point.
EventNarrative: People in Pilot Point reported very large waves, described as impressive, moving in with the incoming high tide. Flooding occurred up to the old cannery.

EpisodeNarrative: A storm moved to the Aleutians producing strong wind and snow that resulted in a blizzard across portions of the central Aleutians.

A very dynamic storm system brought a variety of severe weather impacts to the South Plains of west Texas late on the 27th. ||Moist and sub-freezing upslope northeasterly flow behind a cold front resulted in persistent ice fog through much of the day over the extreme southeastern Texas Panhandle, particularly along the Caprock Escarpment. Although ice accumulated on most exposed surfaces, no adverse impacts were reported.||By late afternoon, weather impacts became much more intense and diverse. An area of heavy snow developed over the extreme southwestern Texas Panhandle and the northwestern South Plains. The area of wintry precipitation quickly moved northeastward, but not before accumulating snows occurred over the area and resulted in treacherous travel conditions. Roadways, including major interstate highways, became snowpacked - and remained dangerous through much of the morning hours on the 28th. ||Reported snow accumulations follow:  4 inches at Happy (Swisher County), 3 inches at Lazbuddie (Parmer County), 3 inches at Tulia (Swisher County), 2 inches at Nazareth (Castro County), 1 inch at Dimmitt (Castro County), 1 inch at Plainview (Hale County), and 1 inch at Silverton (Briscoe County).||South of the snow band, strong winds advected eastward behind a dryline-like feature that moved over the western and central South Plains. Wind gusts in excess of 40 mph were recorded at a number of Texas Tech University West Texas Mesonet sites over the western South Plains. Wind contributed to the failure of a metal shed building in northwest Lubbock. In addition, two non-mesocyclonic tornadoes were observed and photographed in the Lubbock vicinity. These tornadoes developed near a deepening surface low and its associated surface boundaries, and beneath towering cumulus clouds within a strongly unstable low-level airmass. No measurable precipitation occurred in association with the tornadic cumuliform clouds.

A wintry mix of precipitation resulting in slick roads was a contributing factor in a traffic accident resulting in one fatality and three injuries (all indirect) in Cheshire County.

A winter storm system over the Four Corners region tracked east toward the northern Texas Panhandle during the nighttime hours and produced heavy snow by morning. Four inches of snow was reported at Spearman in Hansford County and four inches of snow was reported fifteen miles south of Perryton in Ochiltree County.
EventNarrative: Four inches of snow was reported at Spearman.

EventNarrative: Strong winds contributed to the failure of a metal shed in the northwestern portions of Lubbock. The shed, which was not tied down, was blown up against a nearby home and resulted in minor structural damage. No other damage occurred in the immediate area, and nearby observations from the Texas Tech University West Texas Mesonet failed to show evidence of high winds. It is estimated that gusts were locally in excess of 40 mph. Similar wind speeds were common west of the city as a dryline-like feature translated eastward across the region.

The tornado apparently developed as towering cumuliform clouds formed above an advancing low-level boundary. Witnesses report that the tornado persisted for five minutes. No damage was reported.

EpisodeNarrative: One inch of snow and icy roads contributed to a one vehicle accident in which a nineteen year old woman was killed.
EventNarrative: One inch of snow on U.S. Highway 287 near the Canadian River Bridge contributed to icy conditions which led to a one vehicle accident in which a nineteen year old female was killed. The vehicle in which she was driving in rolled over. Three other passengers in the vehicle were injured.

EpisodeNarrative: Surface low pressure developed and moved over the Red River region of Oklahoma and pushed east into southeast Oklahoma. Precipitation developed north of this low pressure during the late evening of the 27th and early morning of the 28th. Sufficient cold air was in place that a variety of winter weather moved over the northern half of Oklahoma. Mostly snow fell over the northern third to fourth of Oklahoma, with a wide swath of one to three inches accumulating. Minimal travel impact occurred with minor injuries. Monetary damages were estimated.
EventNarrative: One and a half of inches of snow was reported on the ground near Orienta.

A vigorous upper level trough with an associated strong Pacific cold front brought strong surface winds to far west Texas during the late afternoon and early evening hours. Windows were broken and power poles were knocked down in the El Paso area.
EventNarrative: Winds gusting to around 60 mph broke windows in downtown El Paso and knocked down power poles elsewhere in the city.

EpisodeNarrative: Dangerous Surf conditions led to the death of a diver in Carmel.
EventNarrative: A diver was found dead off Monastery Beach in Carmel - shortly after entering the water. Conditions were extremely dangerous with strong energy waves and heights over 10 feet. Water temperatures were in the lower 50s.

EpisodeNarrative: Low pressure moved rapidly from the southern Plains to eastern Missouri and then to southern lower Michigan. This spread a large area of snow across the region on December 28 2007, with the snow falling for about 6 to 12 hours. The storm produced several hours of moderate to heavy snow, with rates of an inch or more per hour in the heavy snow bands. Widespread 3 to 6 inches of accumulation occurred, with a band of 6 to 7 inches falling from the Quad Cities to Freeport, Illinois. The wind was relatively light during the event, so blowing and drifting was not an issue.

A complex storm system took shape at the end of December and brought a round of elevated hail storms to the region. The hail storms occurred as a warm front and deeper moisture surged northward during the early morning hours, generally between 1 and 6 am and were scattered about the forecast area. The hail stones ranged between penny and quarter size and caused little to no damage.
EventNarrative: A swath of penny to quarter size hail fell from Merigold to the intersection of Parchman Road and the Sunflower County line.

A moist pacific weather system tracked through the inland northwest where heavy snow fell in the Central Idaho Panhandle.  Snow accumulations include eight to ten inches in the mountains, with Kellogg also picking up four inches.

A complex storm system took shape at the end of December and brought a round of elevated hail storms to the region. The hail storms occurred as a warm front and deeper moisture surged northward during the early morning hours, generally between 1 and 6 am and were scattered about the forecast area. The hail stones ranged between penny and quarter size and caused little to no damage.
EventNarrative: A swath of penny to quarter sized hail fell from just east of French Camp to about 6 miles north of Weir.

A prolonged fall of light to moderate snow fell across all of south-central and southeast Wisconsin, resulting in accumulations of 3 to 8 inches.  The wind was a non-factor, and roads were reported to be in good condition during this event, consequentely the impact of society was minimal, and this was not classified as a Heavy Snow event.  Specific snowfall totals include 8.1 at Cedarburg; 8.0 at Dousman, North Prairie, East Troy, Hales Corner, Watertown, and Allenton; 7.8 at Waterford; 7.5 at Howards Grove and Palmyra; 6.8 at Stoughton and Beloit College; 6 at Ashford and Monroe; 5.7 at South Wayne; 5.5 at Milwaukee Mitchell Field and Columbus; 5.1 at Madison Truax Field, 5 at Twin Lakes; 4.2 at Redstorn Lake north of La Valle, 4 in the southeast corner of Iowa County; and 3.7 at Markesan.  Newspapers indicated that there the usual vehicle accidents in all affected counties.  The 5.5 measured at Milwaukee was a new record for December 28th, breaking the old record of 5.3 set in 1968.  In Germantown (Washington Co.), the weight of the snow broke a 10 diameter tree branch which fell onto a vehicle.  Luckily there was only minor scratches on the vehicle.  Synoptically, low pressure tracked from Missouri to the lower part of Lake Michigan and then lower Michigan.

A prolonged fall of light to moderate snow fell across all of south-central and southeast Wisconsin, resulting in accumulations of 3 to 8 inches.  The wind was a non-factor, and roads were reported to be in good condition during this event, consequentely the impact of society was minimal, and this was not classified as a Heavy Snow event.  Specific snowfall totals include 8.1 at Cedarburg; 8.0 at Dousman, North Prairie, East Troy, Hales Corner, Watertown, and Allenton; 7.8 at Waterford; 7.5 at Howards Grove and Palmyra; 6.8 at Stoughton and Beloit College; 6 at Ashford and Monroe; 5.7 at South Wayne; 5.5 at Milwaukee Mitchell Field and Columbus; 5.1 at Madison Truax Field, 5 at Twin Lakes; 4.2 at Redstorn Lake north of La Valle, 4 in the southeast corner of Iowa County; and 3.7 at Markesan. Low pressure moved rapidly from the southern Plains to eastern Missouri and then to southern lower Michigan. This spread a large area of snow across the region on December 28 2007, with the snow falling for about 6 to 12 hours. The storm produced several hours of moderate to heavy snow, with rates of an inch or more per hour in the heavy snow bands. Widespread 3 to 6 inches of accumulation occurred, with a band of 6 to 7 inches falling from the Quad Cities to Freeport, Illinois. The wind was relatively light during the event, so blowing and drifting was not an issue.

As a cold front moved across the coastal waters, a few storms became strong and produced wind gusts over 40 mph.
EventNarrative: An oil rig in a local tv station network recorded a wind gust of 48 mph.

EpisodeNarrative: A strong cold front was approaching the area from the west early on the 28th.  A deep upper-level trough was moving into the mid-south.  Unusually warm, moist Gulf air was present over the region in advance of these systems.  Widespread showers and thunderstorms spread across the area from the southwest early in the day and moved rapidly northeast, bringing beneficial rains to much of north and central Georgia.  However, an isolated severe thunderstorm was reported in west central Georgia in Heard county before daybreak.
EventNarrative: A storm spotter observed nickel-sized hail in the Franklin area.

EpisodeNarrative: A complex storm system took shape at the end of December and brought a round of elevated hail storms to the region. The hail storms occurred as a warm front and deeper moisture surged northward during the early morning hours, generally between 1 and 6 am and were scattered about the forecast area. The hail stones ranged between penny and quarter size and caused little to no damage.

A potent upper level disturbance lifted across Michigan on the 28th, bringing a relatively short period of heavy snow.  Accumulations of five to six inches were common across almost all of Northern Michigan, falling in just six hours.  Cross Village had the most accumulation with just short of nine inches, while Gaylord, Suttons Bay, McKinley, and Moran were around eight inches.

A cool storm system with rain and thick cloud cover kept daily maximum temperatures over the northern Sacramento Valley in the upper 30s on December 28th and 29th. Daily low maximum temperature records were set in both Redding and Red Bluff on December 29th.
EventNarrative: A new daily low maximum temperature record of 38 degrees was set at Redding Airport, breaking the old record of 40 degrees set in 2003. ||A new daily low maximum temperature record of 39 degrees was set at Red Bluff Airport, breaking the old record of 42 degrees set in 1988.

EpisodeNarrative: An upper level disturbance coupled with surface low pressure across Ontario on December 28th moved across Quebec during the early morning hours of the 29th. Snow overspread Vermont just after midnight on the 29th and continued through daybreak. Accumulating snow mainly fell across north central and northeast Vermont, including the western slopes of the northern Green Mountains, where 2 to 5 inches of snow fell. Some specific snowfall totals included; 5 inches in Canaan (Essex county), 4 inches in Island Pond (Essex county) and Newport (Orleans county) with 3 inches in Sutton and Wheelock (Caledonia county), Hanksville (eastern Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county) and Worcester (Washington county).

Some specific snowfall totals included; 5 inches in Canaan (Essex county), 4 inches in Island Pond (Essex county) and Newport (Orleans county) with 3 inches in Sutton and Wheelock (Caledonia county), Hanksville (eastern Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county) and Worcester (Washington county).
A storm system brought heavy snow to portions of the Rocky Mountain Front. Snow amounts in excess of 10 inches were reported.
EventNarrative: Twelve inches of snow was reported at the Copper Camp SNOTEL site (elevation 6950 feet).

EpisodeNarrative: On December 29 and 30, moist northwesterly flow persisted over the northern Rockies. During this period, a series of shortwave disturbances moved through and produced heavy snow accumulations and strong winds across Western Montana.
EventNarrative: Spotters from Thompson Falls and Evaro reported 9.5 and 10.5 inches of new snowfall respectively. In addition, Lookout Pass reported wind gusts up to 22 mph. Pardee and Plains also reported gusty winds to 20 mph.

EpisodeNarrative: On December 29 and 30, moist northwesterly flow persisted over the northern Rockies. During this period, a series of shortwave disturbances moved through and produced heavy snow accumulations and strong winds across Western Montana.
EventNarrative: Snowfall amounts received from spotters and automated weather stations in this zone ranged from 5 to 20 inches. Some of the more notable amounts were 14 inches at Libby, 9 inches at Troy, 10 inches at Bull Lake and 20 inches at Grave Creek.

EpisodeNarrative: On December 29 and 30, moist northwesterly flow persisted over the northern Rockies. During this period, a series of shortwave disturbances moved through and produced heavy snow accumulations and strong winds across North Central Idaho.
EventNarrative: Trained spotters reported between 8 and 15 inches of new snowfall accumulations in Pierce, Weippe, Headquarters and Cardiff. In addition, wind gusts to 27 mph were observed at nearby weather observation stations. Spotters near Weippe also reported blowing and drifting snow.

EpisodeNarrative: On December 29 and 30, moist northwesterly flow persisted over the northern Rockies. During this period, a series of shortwave disturbances moved through and produced heavy snow accumulations and strong winds across Western Montana.
EventNarrative: Automated weather observation station at Seeley Lake reported 16 inches of new snowfall. A snowfall reporter in Condon reported 8 inches of new snow. In addition, weather observation stations in Greenough and Lower Rock Creek reported gusty winds to 21 and 23 mph respectively.

EpisodeNarrative: On December 29 and 30, moist northwesterly flow persisted over the northern Rockies. During this period, a series of shortwave disturbances moved through and produced heavy snow accumulations and strong winds across North Central Idaho.
EventNarrative: Trained spotters reported between 7 and 18 inches of new snowfall accumulations in Elk City, Dixie, and Lolo Pass. In addition, wind gusts to 40 mph were observed at a nearby weather observation station at Lodgepole. Blowing and drifting snow was reported by spotters in Elk City.

EpisodeNarrative: On December 29 and 30, moist northwesterly flow persisted over the northern Rockies. During this period, a series of shortwave disturbances moved through and produced heavy snow accumulations and strong winds across Western Montana.
EventNarrative: Highway 2 corridor between Hungry Horse and Marias Pass received 8.5 to 18 inches of new snowfall. In addition, winds to 20 mph were reported along this route from the Fielding RAWS weather station.

EpisodeNarrative: A Pacific storm system brought heavy snow to the mountains and mountain valleys of northern Utah.
EventNarrative: Snowbasin received 32 inches of snow for the storm total, while Ben Lomond and Tony Grove SNOTEL sites received about 35 inches each.

EpisodeNarrative: Persistent moist westerly flow from the Pacific Ocean created a prolonged period of snow and gusty wind across western Wyoming.  Wind gusts of 25 to 35 mph were common along with heavy snow, which combined to cause white-out conditions at times.  Snowfall totals in the Jackson and Star valleys generally ranged from six to eleven inches.  Amounts of one to two feet of snow fell in the Teton, Gros Ventre, Wyoming, and Salt River mountain ranges.

EpisodeNarrative: An isolated severe thunderstorm produced large hail over the southern Upstate of South Carolina around mid-day.

Yet another in a series of cold, moist Pacific frontal systems brought heavy snow to the Cascades. Westerly flow behind the advancing cold front orographically enhanced snowfall potential for this storm. This storm was the fourth storm in six days to bring heavy snow to the Cascades, continuing to build the steadily increasing mountain snow pack.
EventNarrative: Nineteen inches total snowfall accumulation was reported at Timberline Lodge on Mt. Hood.

EpisodeNarrative: A combination of a moist zonal flow and strong upper level jet stream brought extensive blowing and drifting snow to the North-Central Mountains of Colorado.  Wind sensors above timberline measured peak gusts from 75 to 92 mph.  The combination of snow and wind resulted in whiteout conditions and a high avalanche danger along the Interstate 70 Corridor, from Floyd Hill to Vail.  As a result, the interstate was closed for approximately 24 hours.  Other closures included:  Berthoud and Rabbit Ears Passes on U.S. Highway 40; Loveland Pass on U.S. Highway 6; Cameron Pass on State Highway 14; Kenosha Pass on U.S. Highway 285; U.S. Highways 287 and 85 near the Wyoming Border.   ||The American Red Cross opened 9 shelters in Summit County for stranded motorists; where more than 2,000 people took shelter.  Loveland Ski Area was forced to close for the day because employees and skiers couldn't get to it.  Tow truck drivers spent much of their time rescuing stranded motorists.  In Grand County, a snowmobiler was injured when he triggered an avalanche.  He was knocked unconscious and buried under 3 feet of snow.  Fortunately, he suffered only a separated shoulder.  ||Peak wind gust reports included:  92 mph at Niwot Ridge; 89 mph at Mines peak; 87 mph at Georgetown; 80 mph at Berthoud and Loveland Passes; 75 mph at Gunsight; 60 mph at Copper Mountain.  Storm totals during the 2-day period were light to moderate with amounts ranging from 5 to 10 inches.  The exception occurred at the Columbine Snotel where 15 inches of snowfall was measured.
EventNarrative: Strong winds caused whiteout conditions, forcing the closure of Rabbit Ears Pass on State Highway 14.

EpisodeNarrative: A moist pacific system moved into the inland northwest with about an inch of snow falling on the Palouse on the 29th and early on the 30th. Wind gusts to near 45 MPH with the storm occurred throughout the day on the 30th, creating areas of blowing snow.  Winds created significant drifting of snow and whiteout conditions, which closed Highway 195 just south of Pullman to the top of Lewiston Hill.  State Route 272 from Colfax to the Idaho Border was also closed.  Winds at the Pullman Airport gusted to near 45 MPH.

A moist pacific system tracked through north Idaho bringing heavy snow.  The highest accumulations occurred in the Central Panhandle Mountains where seven to 12 inches accumulated.  In the North Idaho Panhandle, accumulations in the valleys ranged from four to six inches.

An intense pacific storm brought heavy snow and strong winds to southeast Idaho.  Blizzard conditions occurred across much of the southern and eastern highlands with many road closures.  Heavy snow fell in parts of the central mountains and Upper Snake River Highlands.
EventNarrative: Five to eight inches of snow combined with strong winds closed roads in the Upper Snake River Highlands.  State Highway 32 from Driggs to Ashton closed due to drifting snow across the roadway on the morning of the 30th.

EventNarrative: Twelve inches of snow was recorded at the Howell Canyon SNOTEL site.  Blizzard conditions were reported in the eastern parts of the South Central Highlands.  South bound Interstate 15 was closed due to the drifting snow on the 30th.

White out conditions were reported during the morning of the 30th in Wayan, Chesterfield, and Grace.  Back roads were closed.  US Highway 26 was closed from Ririe to the Wyoming state line due to the drifting snow.

The Bear Lake County sherrif's department reported white out conditions throughout the county. EventNarrative: Idaho road department reported 8 inches of new snow at Lost Trail Pass at 0930 am MST on December 30. Snowfall totals for this event ranged from 7.5 inches at Gibbonsville to 16 inches at Lost Trail Pass.

A low pressure system brought mixed precipitation across Berks County, the Lehigh Valley and the Poconos. The combination of snow, sleet and freezing rain fell and accumulations averaged one to four inches with the highest amounts in the Poconos. ||Precipitation started as rain in Berks County and the Lehigh Valley and as snow in the Poconos during the afternoon on the 30th. As warmer air moved in aloft, the snow changed to sleet and then freezing rain in the Poconos during the evening of the 30th. As the low pressure pulled away, precipitation changed back to snow in the Poconos late that evening and then later that night in the Lehigh Valley and Berks County. The snow ended by 6 a.m. EST on the 31st. Most of the traffic related accidents occurred in the Poconos, as the plateau region reported the most. There were two serious crashes in the area of Interstate 80 and Interstate 380 in Monroe County. ||Specific accumulations included 4.0 inches in Albrightsville (Carbon County) and Pocono Summit (Monroe County), 3.7 inches in Saylorsburg (Monroe County), 2.0 inches in Jim Thorpe (Carbon County), 1.6 inches in New Tripoli (Lehigh County), 0.7 inches at the Lehigh Valley International Airport and 0.4 inches in Hamburg (Berks County).||The precipitation was caused by a low pressure system that formed over the southeastern states early on December 30th. It moved northeast and at 7 p.m. EST on the 30th it was just east of Elizabeth City, North Carolina. The low moved northeast and at 1 a.m. EST on the 31st, it was just east of Delaware. It accelerated eastnortheastward and by 7 a.m. EST on the 31st was already about 125 miles southeast of Cape Cod, Massachusetts. The fast movement prevented precipitation from becoming heavy.

An area of low pressure developed near the central Gulf coast states and tracked northeast along a nearly stationary front across south Georgia during the late afternoon of December 30th.  Pre-frontal storms developed across south Georgia where surface based lifted indices were near -2 to -3. Storms had persistent mesocyclone rotations and several storms developed bow echo signatures with outbound velocities around 40 to 50 knots along the leading edge of the bow around 3-4 kft above ground level prior to warning issuance.
EventNarrative: The county dispatch reported several trees were blown down along Quincey Batten Loop near State Road 206. The cost of tree removal was estimated.

EpisodeNarrative: Upslope-enhanced snowfall developed across the northern Black Hills late in the day and persisted through the night. As much as eight inches of snow were reported west of Lead.

There were two serious crashes in the area of Interstate 80 and Interstate 380 in Monroe County. ||Specific accumulations included 4.0 inches in Albrightsville (Carbon County) and Pocono Summit (Monroe County), 3.7 inches in Saylorsburg (Monroe County), 2.0 inches in Jim Thorpe (Carbon County), 1.6 inches in New Tripoli (Lehigh County), 0.7 inches at the Lehigh Valley International Airport and 0.4 inches in Hamburg (Berks County).||The precipitation was caused by a low pressure system that formed over the southeastern states early on December 30th. It moved northeast and at 7 p.m. EST on the 30th it was just east of Elizabeth City, North Carolina. The low moved northeast and at 1 a.m. EST on the 31st, it was just east of Delaware. It accelerated eastnortheastward and by 7 a.m. EST on the 31st was already about 125 miles southeast of Cape Cod, Massachusetts. The fast movement prevented precipitation from becoming heavy.
A strong cold front pushed through southeastern Georgia resulting in a couple strong thunderstorms.
EventNarrative: Eight homes were reported to have sustained damage by debris and tree branches. One home had brick siding separate from the home. Several trees were reported to have snapped off at the base.

EpisodeNarrative: A low pressure system tracked northeast from the Carolina coast to east of Cape Cod from the afternoon of the 29th through the morning of the 30th. Snow, mixed with sleet at times, spread into northeast Pennsylvania during the evening on Sunday and continued overnight before tapering off Monday morning. Snowfall amounts ranged around 7 inches in Susquehanna County.
EventNarrative: Snowfall amounts across the county ranged from 5 to 8 inches.

A low pressure system over eastern North Carolina spread precipitation across the Mid Atlantic on December 30th. As the low pulled north and intensified off Cape Cod, colder air was brought across the region, causing rain to turn to a wintry mix and finally snow across the region during the evening and overnight hours.
EventNarrative: A Trained Spotter measured 1.8 inches of snow in Hancock, MD.

EpisodeNarrative: A low pressure system tracked northeast along the Atlantic Coast from Sunday, December 30th, into Monday, December 31st, while intensifying. This storm system brought a swath of moderate to heavy snow to eastern New York and western New England Sunday night into Monday morning.||Across eastern New York, snowfall amounts ranged from 6 to 12 inches across the southern and western Adirondacks and Mohawk Valley, the Lake George and Saratoga region, the Helderbergs, the eastern Catskills and within the immediate Capital Region. Slightly lower amounts occurred well to the north, within the southern Adirondacks, where 3 to 7 inches fell. Lighter amounts also occurred across the mid Hudson Valley region, where generally 1 to 5 inches fell.||The moderate to heavy snow led to hazardous driving conditions during the Monday morning commute, and resulted in numerous businesses to close, or delay opening on Monday morning.||Most schools were already closed due to the Holiday break.
EventNarrative: Snow developed during Sunday evening on December 30th, and ended during the mid morning hours of Monday December 31st. Total snowfall amounts ranged from 3 to 6 inches.||The snow led to hazardous driving conditions during the Monday morning commute.

EpisodeNarrative: A surface low across the southeast United States on the morning of December 30th moved along the Mid-Atlantic coast during the evening and night of the 30th to southeast of Cape Cod by daybreak on the 31st. Snow overspread southern Vermont before Midnight on the 31st and continued until daybreak on the 31st, when it tapered to snow showers before ending by mid-morning. Snowfall amounts across southern Vermont were generally 5 to 8 inches. Some specific snowfall totals included; 9 inches in Killington (eastern Rutland county), 6 inches in Pawlet and Rutland (Rutland county) as well as Andover, Ludlow and Springfield (Windsor county).

EventNarrative: Low temperatures in ORZ021 ranged from 28 to 32 degrees.

Areas of dense fog developed across portions of north-central Maryland during the early morning hours of December 31st. Visibilities were often reduced to a quarter mile or less. Temperatures during the overnight hours fell into the lower 30s, causing fog to freeze onto some surfaces. The fog and glaze of ice caused significant travel problems. Over 100 accidents were reported on Interstate 70, US 340 and US 15. One fatality was reported in Frederick County.
EventNarrative: Dense fog and freezing fog was reported by the ASOS at the Hagerstown Regional Airport.

EventNarrative: Dense fog and freezing fog was reported by the AWOS at the Frederick Municipal Airport. Dense freezing fog and icy roadways caused numerous travel problems in Frederick County. Over 100 vehicle crashes were reported during the early and mid morning hours. The westbound lanes of Interstate 70 were closed for at least 9 hours due to a crash. A newspaper reported that a local firefighter was killed about 4:30 AM on the US 15 bridge over the Potomac River at Point of Rocks.

Low pressure developed over the south central U.S. and intensified over Missouri.  The low tracked northeast into southern Indiana by late on the evening of the 31st.  A narrow swath of heavy snow fell to the north of the low pressure track.  General snow amounts of 1 to 4 inches were reported over the southeast quarter of the state.  A small area of 6 to 7 inch snowfall brushed the far southeast part of the Des Moines CWA in Appanoose and Davis Counties.

A combination of a moist zonal flow and strong upper level jet stream brought extensive blowing and drifting snow to the North-Central Mountains of Colorado.  Wind sensors above timberline measured peak gusts from 75 to 92 mph.  The combination of snow and wind resulted in whiteout conditions and a high avalanche danger along the Interstate 70 Corridor, from Floyd Hill to Vail.  As a result, the interstate was closed for approximately 24 hours.  Other closures included:  Berthoud and Rabbit Ears Passes on U.S. Highway 40; Loveland Pass on U.S. Highway 6; Cameron Pass on State Highway 14; Kenosha Pass on U.S. Highway 285; U.S. Highways 287 and 85 near the Wyoming Border.   ||The American Red Cross opened 9 shelters in Summit County for stranded motorists; where more than 2,000 people took shelter.  Loveland Ski Area was forced to close for the day because employees and skiers couldn't get to it.  Tow truck drivers spent much of their time rescuing stranded motorists.  In Grand County, a snowmobiler was injured when he triggered an avalanche.  He was knocked unconscious and buried under 3 feet of snow.  Fortunately, he suffered only a separated shoulder.  ||Peak wind gust reports included:  92 mph at Niwot Ridge; 89 mph at Mines peak; 87 mph at Georgetown; 80 mph at Berthoud and Loveland Passes; 75 mph at Gunsight; 60 mph at Copper Mountain.  Storm totals during the 2-day period were light to moderate with amounts ranging from 5 to 10 inches.  The exception occurred at the Columbine Snotel where 15 inches of snowfall was measured.
EventNarrative: A snowmobiler was injured when he triggered an avalanche. He was knocked unconscious and buried under 3 feet of snow. Fortunately, he suffered only a separated shoulder.

Three snowboarders were caught in an avalanche, leading to one fatality.
EventNarrative: Three experienced snowmobilers were riding in Smith Basin, about 15 miles east-northeast of the Co-op trailhead, when an avalanche engulfed all three of them. Two of them were able to swim out of the snow, but the third, a 41 year-old male, was buried for at least 40 minutes, and died before they could dig him out. For the state of Utah, this was the third avalanche fatality in 8 days. It was also the 7th avalanche fatality for the 2007 calendar year, the most in one year since records have been kept, starting in 1958.

EpisodeNarrative: Offshore flow resulted in high winds in the Santa Ana Mountains and Foothills. Wind gusts in excess of 58 mph were reported at Fremont Canyon and Tonner Canyon. It was at Tonner Canyon where a peak wind of 72 mph was observed. Damage consisted mainly of broken tree limbs and branches.
EventNarrative: A 72 mph wind gusts was measured by the Tonner Canyon RAWS.

EpisodeNarrative: On the morning of 12/31 a storm was developing well southwest of the Panhandle. Although this system remained nearly stationary, extreme surface pressure gradients developed against arctic high pressure over the Yukon during new year's eve. The storm weakened rapidly later on new year's day.
EventNarrative: Sitka observed a measured gust of 48 MPH at 2200 on 12/31. Analyses showed extreme surface pressure gradients on 12/31 and 1/1/08. A marine observation at Cape Decision had a measured gust of 63 knots at 2200 on new year's eve.

EventNarrative: Craig reported very windy with higher gusts from 2000 on new year's eve  through the morning of 1/1/08. A marine observation at Cape Decision had a measured gust of 63 knots at 2200 on new year's eve. Hydaburg observed a gust of 51 knots around midnight on new year's eve.

EpisodeNarrative: Heavy snow moved into southern lower Michigan during the early evening hours of New Year's Eve, impacting New Year's travel plans by creating very hazardous travel conditions in heavy snow and snow covered roads.  Many locations across southern Michigan reported total snowfall of 7 to 10 inches, with as much as 11.5 inches reported three miles south southeast of Jackson.
EventNarrative: This heavy snow event continued into the early morning hours on New Year's Day.
